73
00:03:29,100 --> 00:03:32,220
So the key is really
matching your capacity

74
00:03:32,220 --> 00:03:33,430
and your utilization

75
00:03:34,440 --> 00:03:35,490
so you can reduce your costs

76
00:03:35,490 --> 00:03:37,200
while reducing or eliminating

77
00:03:37,200 --> 00:03:38,880
your performance bottle
necks at the same time.

78
00:03:38,880 --> 00:03:40,293
That's basically the key.

79
00:03:42,300 --> 00:03:44,970
Now, there's six things
that I've identified

80
00:03:44,970 --> 00:03:47,550
because I've looked at a lot
of migrations since then.

81
00:03:47,550 --> 00:03:50,190
What's different between the
experience that I went through

82
00:03:50,190 --> 00:03:52,560
and the experience that I
see on a almost daily basis.

83
00:03:52,560 --> 00:03:55,770
And I hear from customers
on a almost daily basis.

84
00:03:55,770 --> 00:03:57,870
And to be clear, some
of them are successful,

85
00:03:57,870 --> 00:03:59,010
but not all of them are.

86
00:03:59,010 --> 00:04:01,500
And it's my goal to make
all of them successful.

87
00:04:01,500 --> 00:04:04,290
So what are the successful
ones have in common?

88
00:04:04,290 --> 00:04:06,543
Well, I've identified these six pillars.

89
00:04:07,830 --> 00:04:09,990
First is they have a compelling why.

90
00:04:09,990 --> 00:04:12,870
Now, this can't be because
we wanna save money

91
00:04:12,870 --> 00:04:15,030
or because the CEO said so.

92
00:04:15,030 --> 00:04:17,370
It has to be something that the people

93
00:04:17,370 --> 00:04:20,850
who you're depending on,
hopefully your own employees,

94
00:04:20,850 --> 00:04:22,380
are going to really care about.

95
00:04:22,380 --> 00:04:23,940
This should be your company's mission.

96
00:04:23,940 --> 00:04:28,940
This should be, you know,
something that drives them.

97
00:04:29,340 --> 00:04:30,495
Because when things get hard,

98
00:04:30,495 --> 00:04:33,420
they're gonna need to be
able to push through that.

99
00:04:33,420 --> 00:04:35,100
Two is utilize constraints,

100
00:04:35,100 --> 00:04:37,380
and this is one that
could be counterintuitive.

101
00:04:37,380 --> 00:04:39,480
You know, when people hear about my story,

102
00:04:40,650 --> 00:04:44,130
you know, 12 month deadline,
no budget, frozen headcount,

103
00:04:44,130 --> 00:04:46,890
and then still was able to be successful,

104
00:04:46,890 --> 00:04:49,350
I sometimes say "That's
why we were successful."

105
00:04:49,350 --> 00:04:51,210
A lot of the migrations that I see fail

106
00:04:51,210 --> 00:04:53,730
are the ones that have too many resources,

107
00:04:53,730 --> 00:04:55,860
and we'll get into that
a little bit more later.

108
00:04:55,860 --> 00:04:57,450
Third is the invest in people,

109
00:04:57,450 --> 00:04:59,580
and this one should be a no brainer.

110
00:04:59,580 --> 00:05:01,740
The more skilled your
workforce is in cloud,

111
00:05:01,740 --> 00:05:03,900
the better they're gonna be
at migrating to the cloud

112
00:05:03,900 --> 00:05:05,400
and at operating in the cloud.

113
00:05:05,400 --> 00:05:09,090
And so the investment is completely key.

114
00:05:09,090 --> 00:05:13,020
Building momentum in a
migration or any transformation,

115
00:05:13,020 --> 00:05:16,230
and a lot of this applies to
AI transformations as well,

116
00:05:16,230 --> 00:05:19,860
it's super key because things
tend to start off slow,

117
00:05:19,860 --> 00:05:23,340
and then as you start
winning that compounds.

118
00:05:23,340 --> 00:05:26,220
And inertia can compound as well,

119
00:05:26,220 --> 00:05:28,710
you could just keep going slow as well.

120
00:05:28,710 --> 00:05:31,269
Embracing simplicity is is the next one.

121
00:05:31,269 --> 00:05:32,850
And I would say this is probably

122
00:05:32,850 --> 00:05:35,100
the biggest one that I see violated.

123
00:05:35,100 --> 00:05:40,100
I see, excess complexity in
my opinion, is the root cause

124
00:05:40,110 --> 00:05:43,590
of failed migrations and failed
transformations in general.

125
00:05:43,590 --> 00:05:46,530
And so what this means is most
of the things that people do

126
00:05:46,530 --> 00:05:48,450
when they migrate are
simply not necessary.

127
00:05:48,450 --> 00:05:51,570
Or the ones that are necessary,
they're far too complex.

128
00:05:51,570 --> 00:05:52,620
And last but not least,

129
00:05:52,620 --> 00:05:55,530
and this is a hard requirement,
is having strong leadership.

130
00:05:55,530 --> 00:05:57,660
You have to have somebody
who's accountable,

131
00:05:57,660 --> 00:06:00,660
and they have to be, have
the authority to do things

132
00:06:00,660 --> 00:06:02,100
and it doesn't have to
be a lot of authority,

133
00:06:02,100 --> 00:06:03,870
but they need to be accountable

134
00:06:03,870 --> 00:06:05,580
for those things that
they have authority for,

135
00:06:05,580 --> 00:06:07,730
and they need to have
a little bit of guts.

136
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:12,090
So for past seven years, like I said,

137
00:06:12,090 --> 00:06:14,400
I've been talking to
hundreds of executive teams

138
00:06:14,400 --> 00:06:16,350
on the topic of migration

139
00:06:16,350 --> 00:06:21,240
and I hear the same objections
over and over again.

140
00:06:21,240 --> 00:06:22,470
So Live Nation/Ticketmaster,

141
00:06:22,470 --> 00:06:25,890
we were, Live Nation is an
entertainment company, right?

142
00:06:25,890 --> 00:06:28,050
So I'll talk to an energy company,

143
00:06:28,050 --> 00:06:29,460
they'll say, "Well that would never work

144
00:06:29,460 --> 00:06:31,380
for an energy company," right?

145
00:06:31,380 --> 00:06:34,628
So we're special, right?

146
00:06:34,628 --> 00:06:36,600
Or the scope is too big.

147
00:06:36,600 --> 00:06:38,040
So we migrated, you know,

148
00:06:38,040 --> 00:06:42,120
we're $11 billion revenue
runway business at the time,

149
00:06:42,120 --> 00:06:44,730
much more today, but there are companies

150
00:06:44,730 --> 00:06:45,780
that are much bigger than that

151
00:06:45,780 --> 00:06:47,700
and they can very easily say

152
00:06:47,700 --> 00:06:50,010
it would never work at our scale.

153
00:06:50,010 --> 00:06:53,913
And the third most common,
it's almost always these three,

154
00:06:55,050 --> 00:06:57,060
is that we have unique
regulatory requirements.

155
00:06:57,060 --> 00:06:59,220
So like the cloud won't work for us,

156
00:06:59,220 --> 00:07:02,730
or it's hard for us to migrate
that quickly because of that.

157
00:07:02,730 --> 00:07:04,650
But the thing is, when you strip away

158
00:07:04,650 --> 00:07:07,020
all the assumptions and complexity,

159
00:07:07,020 --> 00:07:09,390
cloud migration is really simple.

160
00:07:09,390 --> 00:07:11,460
It's really moving your
applications and data

161
00:07:11,460 --> 00:07:13,410
from one place to another,

162
00:07:13,410 --> 00:07:15,930
sometimes it's a virtualized environment

163
00:07:15,930 --> 00:07:17,010
in your data center,

164
00:07:17,010 --> 00:07:19,290
to a virtualized environment in the cloud.

165
00:07:19,290 --> 00:07:21,810
And yes, maybe it's a
different technology,

166
00:07:21,810 --> 00:07:25,110
but most of us who are
doing cloud migrations,

167
00:07:25,110 --> 00:07:27,120
we've done data center
consolidations in the past,

168
00:07:27,120 --> 00:07:28,170
it's very similar.

169
00:07:28,170 --> 00:07:30,390
It doesn't have to be that much different.

170
00:07:30,390 --> 00:07:35,070
So I could say this with
confidence because I've done it,

171
00:07:35,070 --> 00:07:36,570
but I could say it even
more with confidence now

172
00:07:36,570 --> 00:07:39,300
because I've helped so
many others do it as well.

173
00:07:39,300 --> 00:07:40,500
It really is the simple.

174
00:07:41,490 --> 00:07:44,040
Now there are workloads that
are difficult to migrate,

175
00:07:44,040 --> 00:07:45,510
you know, mainframes for example,

176
00:07:45,510 --> 00:07:47,430
that require full refactor.

177
00:07:47,430 --> 00:07:49,170
But those are unique edge cases.

178
00:07:49,170 --> 00:07:51,273
Those are not the most common.

179
00:07:52,590 --> 00:07:55,890
So a more generalized
approach is a better approach.

180
00:07:55,890 --> 00:07:58,860
Let's manage the exceptions as exceptions.

181
00:07:58,860 --> 00:08:00,060
And let's take the complexity

182
00:08:00,060 --> 00:08:02,373
out of the 99% that could be easy.

183
00:08:04,230 --> 00:08:07,680
So a good migration
framework is universal.

184
00:08:07,680 --> 00:08:10,530
It'll work in every industry
because your servers don't care

185
00:08:10,530 --> 00:08:13,350
what industry your business is in.

186
00:08:13,350 --> 00:08:16,980
It's effective at any scale
because a good framework,

187
00:08:16,980 --> 00:08:19,560
any good framework is
a scalable one, right?

188
00:08:19,560 --> 00:08:23,340
You take something that
works and you scale it up.

189
00:08:23,340 --> 00:08:26,670
And this has been proven with
this methodology as well.

190
00:08:26,670 --> 00:08:28,380
And it should have compliance built in,

191
00:08:28,380 --> 00:08:30,480
a good framework should
not violate compliance,

192
00:08:30,480 --> 00:08:33,933
it should be flexible
enough to handle compliance.

193
00:08:35,010 --> 00:08:38,700
So there's some lessons that I've learned

194
00:08:38,700 --> 00:08:40,200
through this process,

195
00:08:40,200 --> 00:08:42,330
and some of them can be a
little bit counterintuitive.

196
00:08:42,330 --> 00:08:43,680
This is one of them.

197
00:08:43,680 --> 00:08:44,880
You're more likely to fail

198
00:08:44,880 --> 00:08:46,740
from too few constraints
than from too many.

199
00:08:46,740 --> 00:08:48,780
This is one that people find surprising.

200
00:08:48,780 --> 00:08:49,860
It's like, "Wait a minute,

201
00:08:49,860 --> 00:08:51,390
you're gonna take resources away from me

202
00:08:51,390 --> 00:08:52,560
and I'm gonna be more successful."

203
00:08:52,560 --> 00:08:54,150
Yes, that's usually the case.

204
00:08:54,150 --> 00:08:57,360
Most cloud migrations are overfunded

205
00:08:57,360 --> 00:09:00,180
and their deadlines are
way too long in the future.

206
00:09:00,180 --> 00:09:03,210
I had a 12 month deadline,
it took me 17 months.

207
00:09:03,210 --> 00:09:04,163
If I had a 17 month deadline,

208
00:09:04,163 --> 00:09:06,330
I think it would've taken me two years.

209
00:09:06,330 --> 00:09:07,590
If you gave me two years,

210
00:09:07,590 --> 00:09:09,963
maybe it never would've
get done at all, right?

211
00:09:10,830 --> 00:09:15,450
So some of you may be
familiar with Parkinson's Law.

212
00:09:15,450 --> 00:09:18,750
Basically it explains why, in college,

213
00:09:18,750 --> 00:09:21,750
when your homework is due,
you do it, you start it

214
00:09:21,750 --> 00:09:23,760
the night before instead of like a week

215
00:09:23,760 --> 00:09:24,810
when it was assigned.

216
00:09:26,970 --> 00:09:28,470
We typically have too much time

217
00:09:28,470 --> 00:09:29,790
and too many resources do things.

218
00:09:29,790 --> 00:09:31,560
Now you can take this too far,

219
00:09:31,560 --> 00:09:34,800
but work will expand to fill
up that time that you have.

220
00:09:34,800 --> 00:09:37,530
So if you give yourself five
years to do a migration,

221
00:09:37,530 --> 00:09:39,990
it's going to take five years minimum.

222
00:09:39,990 --> 00:09:42,177
Nobody sets out to do
a five year migration

223
00:09:42,177 --> 00:09:44,880
and it takes two years, right?

224
00:09:44,880 --> 00:09:47,160
But you could set out to
do a one year migration,

225
00:09:47,160 --> 00:09:48,120
it take a year and a half,

226
00:09:48,120 --> 00:09:50,010
that's a much more common pattern.

227
00:09:50,010 --> 00:09:53,160
So what this does is when you set

228
00:09:53,160 --> 00:09:55,050
these seemingly unrealistic goals,

229
00:09:55,050 --> 00:09:56,650
it gives you a sense of urgency.

230
00:09:58,440 --> 00:10:00,000
And if you don't have
that sense of urgency,

231
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:02,730
if you have too much time,
you never get started.

232
00:10:02,730 --> 00:10:05,250
If you have too much time,

233
00:10:05,250 --> 00:10:07,500
say you have a hundred things to do,

234
00:10:07,500 --> 00:10:10,170
most of us, we're gonna
pick out of that hundred,

235
00:10:10,170 --> 00:10:12,570
which one to attack first,
the easiest one, right?

236
00:10:12,570 --> 00:10:14,160
Let's just take the easy one off the list.

237
00:10:14,160 --> 00:10:16,950
But if you had to pick
only 10, you're gonna pick

238
00:10:16,950 --> 00:10:19,470
one of the most top 10 impactful ones.

239
00:10:19,470 --> 00:10:21,900
And that's what the sense of
urgency does, the constraint,

240
00:10:21,900 --> 00:10:23,850
it forces you to focus on what matters.

241
00:10:24,840 --> 00:10:29,310
And innovation, why innovate
if you don't have to?

242
00:10:29,310 --> 00:10:30,630
As human beings, we're lazy.

243
00:10:30,630 --> 00:10:33,150
This isn't a bad thing,
it's efficiency, right?

244
00:10:33,150 --> 00:10:35,040
So if it's worked for us in the past,

245
00:10:35,040 --> 00:10:36,450
it's probably gonna work
for us in the future.

246
00:10:36,450 --> 00:10:39,390
So if we've been doing
migrations like this

247
00:10:39,390 --> 00:10:42,450
for this amount of time, why
not keep doing it that way?

248
00:10:42,450 --> 00:10:44,070
Well, the reason is because we can't.

249
00:10:44,070 --> 00:10:48,210
And constraint forces that.

250
00:10:48,210 --> 00:10:50,310
So you're more likely to
succeed with constraints

251
00:10:50,310 --> 00:10:51,143
than you are without.

252
00:10:51,143 --> 00:10:53,220
This is one of my conclusions.

253
00:10:53,220 --> 00:10:56,400
And nobody wants their
budget taken away from them.

254
00:10:56,400 --> 00:10:58,830
Nobody wants to be under
an unrealistic deadline.

255
00:10:58,830 --> 00:11:02,580
But you can, this is where
the innovation comes from

256
00:11:02,580 --> 00:11:04,590
and this is where the
efficiency comes from,

257
00:11:04,590 --> 00:11:07,030
and it makes for a much
more interesting story

258
00:11:07,980 --> 00:11:09,480
when the odds are stacked against you

259
00:11:09,480 --> 00:11:12,540
and you succeed anyway,
and you'd be surprised.

260
00:11:12,540 --> 00:11:17,540
So instead you put
constraints into motion,

261
00:11:19,140 --> 00:11:22,860
and then you find a way.

262
00:11:22,860 --> 00:11:25,080
So a deadline forces you to find a way.

263
00:11:25,080 --> 00:11:27,930
So for me, I had to begin
before I felt ready.

264
00:11:27,930 --> 00:11:29,461
This is something that I was told,

265
00:11:29,461 --> 00:11:32,670
begin before you feel ready, right?

266
00:11:32,670 --> 00:11:36,150
So I was given the mandate
to migrate in December.

267
00:11:36,150 --> 00:11:38,340
I started beginning of January, why?

268
00:11:38,340 --> 00:11:39,480
Because I had 12 months.

269
00:11:39,480 --> 00:11:42,090
I'm not gonna waste any days, right?

270
00:11:42,090 --> 00:11:43,230
I had to focus on what mattered.

271
00:11:43,230 --> 00:11:45,510
I couldn't get distracted by things

272
00:11:45,510 --> 00:11:47,460
and had to work backwards from a goal.

273
00:11:47,460 --> 00:11:49,440
All right, so it's
easy, 12 month deadline,

274
00:11:49,440 --> 00:11:51,270
we're gonna be done by Christmas

275
00:11:51,270 --> 00:11:52,770
and work backwards from there.

276
00:11:53,820 --> 00:11:57,960
So a budget, and more
specifically a budget

277
00:11:57,960 --> 00:11:59,160
that's smaller than you
would like it to be,

278
00:11:59,160 --> 00:12:00,360
forces you to become lean,

279
00:12:00,360 --> 00:12:03,393
forces you to invent and
simplify, as we say at AWS.

280
00:12:04,410 --> 00:12:05,700
You have to find a new way of doing things

281
00:12:05,700 --> 00:12:06,750
because the old way,

282
00:12:06,750 --> 00:12:08,910
we just don't have the
money to do it anymore.

283
00:12:08,910 --> 00:12:11,730
And that's where new things get invented.

284
00:12:11,730 --> 00:12:14,940
And in my case, a limited
headcount, what it did,

285
00:12:14,940 --> 00:12:18,840
it forced me to motivate my existing team.

286
00:12:18,840 --> 00:12:20,100
So I talked about in the beginning

287
00:12:20,100 --> 00:12:21,930
how I had a frozen headcount, no budget.

288
00:12:21,930 --> 00:12:23,730
So I couldn't hire cloud experts

289
00:12:23,730 --> 00:12:25,590
to come in and do the migration.

290
00:12:25,590 --> 00:12:27,840
So I had to develop a skill.

291
00:12:27,840 --> 00:12:29,640
In order to be successful,
I had to develop the skill

292
00:12:29,640 --> 00:12:32,250
of motivating my team, getting
them upskilled very quickly

293
00:12:32,250 --> 00:12:34,560
and enabling them to be successful.

294
00:12:34,560 --> 00:12:38,250
Now, it's not an easy thing to do.

295
00:12:38,250 --> 00:12:40,410
I'll give you the playbook
and I'll answer your questions

296
00:12:40,410 --> 00:12:42,390
and I'll tell you exactly how to do it.

297
00:12:42,390 --> 00:12:45,930
But once you do that, it is
like having a superpower.

298
00:12:45,930 --> 00:12:46,890
When you can take people

299
00:12:46,890 --> 00:12:48,180
who don't have the skill that you need,

300
00:12:48,180 --> 00:12:50,370
and this is applicable
to AI right now too,

301
00:12:50,370 --> 00:12:52,070
everybody's looking for AI talent.

302
00:12:53,190 --> 00:12:55,860
Good luck hiring those people,
they're in high demand.

303
00:12:55,860 --> 00:12:57,540
But you could take the people you have

304
00:12:57,540 --> 00:12:59,190
and if you can get them interested in it

305
00:12:59,190 --> 00:13:02,064
and you can get them able to learn it,

306
00:13:02,064 --> 00:13:04,230
and then you can get them able to use it

307
00:13:04,230 --> 00:13:07,440
and in a meaningful way
within your organization,

308
00:13:07,440 --> 00:13:09,660
you could have an endless
pipeline of talent.

309
00:13:09,660 --> 00:13:11,280
And that is, as a leader,

310
00:13:11,280 --> 00:13:13,853
it's one of the most liberating
feelings you can have.

311
00:13:15,510 --> 00:13:20,313
So one of the other things that I see,

312
00:13:22,350 --> 00:13:24,990
I would say anti-pattern is conflating,

313
00:13:24,990 --> 00:13:26,070
and this one's a little controversial,

314
00:13:26,070 --> 00:13:28,020
conflating migration and modernization.

315
00:13:29,040 --> 00:13:31,089
The way I look at it is this, migrating,

316
00:13:31,089 --> 00:13:33,690
if people are having a hard time migrating

317
00:13:33,690 --> 00:13:35,220
and people are having a
hard time modernizing,

318
00:13:35,220 --> 00:13:36,360
if you combine both of them,

319
00:13:36,360 --> 00:13:38,250
it's like complexity times complexity.

320
00:13:38,250 --> 00:13:41,160
So your odds of success go down.

321
00:13:41,160 --> 00:13:43,500
And then the common objection

322
00:13:43,500 --> 00:13:46,950
is, "Well, a lift and
shift gives you no value."

323
00:13:46,950 --> 00:13:48,450
Well first of all, I'd argue that,

324
00:13:48,450 --> 00:13:49,283
because your data's in the cloud

325
00:13:49,283 --> 00:13:51,150
and you can use that for AI workloads

326
00:13:51,150 --> 00:13:53,790
and you can do other things as well.

327
00:13:53,790 --> 00:13:56,220
But I'll largely agree with that.

328
00:13:56,220 --> 00:13:59,250
But I'll also say that you
are more likely to migrate

329
00:13:59,250 --> 00:14:02,070
or modernize more quickly,

330
00:14:02,070 --> 00:14:04,920
like your apps will be more modern

331
00:14:04,920 --> 00:14:07,803
and a date sooner than they would be,

332
00:14:09,030 --> 00:14:11,460
if you were to migrate then modernize,

333
00:14:11,460 --> 00:14:13,800
separate them, decouple them.

334
00:14:13,800 --> 00:14:16,410
Separate the complexity
into different stages.

335
00:14:16,410 --> 00:14:18,060
Your modernization will be done sooner

336
00:14:18,060 --> 00:14:20,280
than if you try to do them
both at the same time.

337
00:14:20,280 --> 00:14:22,320
So migrate so you can modernize sooner.

338
00:14:22,320 --> 00:14:23,153
So you can be in the cloud

339
00:14:23,153 --> 00:14:25,173
and you can use all the
great cloud services.

340
00:14:26,040 --> 00:14:29,617
So this is a quote, this
is me from way long ago.

341
00:14:29,617 --> 00:14:32,580
"I don't hire cloud
engineers, I build them."

342
00:14:32,580 --> 00:14:36,960
This is what I would say because
that's how I felt about it.

343
00:14:36,960 --> 00:14:39,690
I was building, it's kind
of a weird way to say it,

344
00:14:39,690 --> 00:14:42,210
but I was building a
pipeline of cloud engineers.

345
00:14:42,210 --> 00:14:45,390
I didn't hire a single
cloud engineer, ever.

346
00:14:45,390 --> 00:14:48,870
I created them out of
people who had IT skills,

347
00:14:48,870 --> 00:14:50,400
but they didn't have cloud talent.

348
00:14:50,400 --> 00:14:53,160
I think we could do this with
AI as well, with any skill.

349
00:14:53,160 --> 00:14:56,940
If they have competency and motivation,

350
00:14:56,940 --> 00:14:59,640
you can build a pipeline
from existing employees.

351
00:14:59,640 --> 00:15:04,140
And so this is the
strategy that I recommend.

352
00:15:04,140 --> 00:15:05,890
Insource your cloud transformation.

353
00:15:08,190 --> 00:15:13,190
If you outsource it, which is
the default that people do,

354
00:15:13,440 --> 00:15:14,940
it's going to be seen as a threat.

355
00:15:14,940 --> 00:15:16,337
And why wouldn't it, right?

356
00:15:16,337 --> 00:15:18,570
'Cause you're basically telling your team

357
00:15:18,570 --> 00:15:20,370
that you have no confidence
that they could do it.

358
00:15:20,370 --> 00:15:22,470
We're bringing in others to do it for you.

359
00:15:23,370 --> 00:15:24,540
It also has a problem

360
00:15:24,540 --> 00:15:26,910
of these people who you bring in to do it,

361
00:15:26,910 --> 00:15:30,090
you're training them and
giving them experience

362
00:15:30,090 --> 00:15:34,080
and then they take that knowledge
with them when they leave.

363
00:15:34,080 --> 00:15:36,300
So in my experience, in my opinion,

364
00:15:36,300 --> 00:15:38,190
they should be paying
you for that experience.

365
00:15:38,190 --> 00:15:39,750
That experience is very valuable.

366
00:15:39,750 --> 00:15:42,210
So you're robbing your
team of that experience.

367
00:15:42,210 --> 00:15:44,160
And then it also incentivizes
short-term thinking.

368
00:15:44,160 --> 00:15:45,300
Because if you think about it,

369
00:15:45,300 --> 00:15:47,460
if you have some hired guns that come in

370
00:15:47,460 --> 00:15:49,560
and they build it and they're gonna leave

371
00:15:49,560 --> 00:15:51,240
and they don't have to maintain it,

372
00:15:51,240 --> 00:15:52,530
they might cut some corners, right?

373
00:15:52,530 --> 00:15:54,270
But if you know you're
gonna build something

374
00:15:54,270 --> 00:15:55,530
and you know you're gonna
have to maintain it,

375
00:15:55,530 --> 00:15:57,180
you're more likely to do it in a way

376
00:15:57,180 --> 00:16:00,655
that is gonna be, have higher
operational excellence,

377
00:16:00,655 --> 00:16:01,755
let's put it that way.

378
00:16:02,610 --> 00:16:07,590
So my thought process here
is insource the migration,

379
00:16:07,590 --> 00:16:09,213
let your own team do it.

380
00:16:10,800 --> 00:16:15,150
You know, you're gonna
bring in external help.

381
00:16:15,150 --> 00:16:18,480
Partners are an excellent resource

382
00:16:18,480 --> 00:16:20,460
and AWS itself is an excellent resource,

383
00:16:20,460 --> 00:16:21,540
and you should bring them in,

384
00:16:21,540 --> 00:16:23,850
but their goal should
be to become irrelevant.

385
00:16:23,850 --> 00:16:26,130
Their goal should be
to upskill your people

386
00:16:26,130 --> 00:16:27,210
because your people are the ones

387
00:16:27,210 --> 00:16:29,910
who are gonna have to
maintain this, right?

388
00:16:29,910 --> 00:16:33,000
And so in DevOps, you say
"You build it, you run it."

389
00:16:33,000 --> 00:16:34,290
I think that should be true

390
00:16:34,290 --> 00:16:35,850
for just about everything, right?

391
00:16:35,850 --> 00:16:37,770
You build it, you run it
with the cloud as well.

392
00:16:37,770 --> 00:16:41,100
Bring in the experts to
transfer the knowledge.

393
00:16:41,100 --> 00:16:45,990
Bring in lower cost resources
to kind of free up their plate

394
00:16:45,990 --> 00:16:48,570
so they can work on it and
do your best as a leader

395
00:16:48,570 --> 00:16:50,020
to allow them to focus on it.

396
00:16:52,470 --> 00:16:56,793
So it has a lot of
advantages when you do this.

397
00:16:58,200 --> 00:16:59,973
Just being purely selfish.

398
00:17:00,930 --> 00:17:02,033
The people that work for you,

399
00:17:02,033 --> 00:17:03,960
or the, all the people
in your organization,

400
00:17:03,960 --> 00:17:04,890
they already know each other.

401
00:17:04,890 --> 00:17:06,810
They already know how
to work with each other.

402
00:17:06,810 --> 00:17:08,520
When you bring in new
people, there's onboarding

403
00:17:08,520 --> 00:17:10,320
and there's complexity with that.

404
00:17:10,320 --> 00:17:11,610
They know how your organization works.

405
00:17:11,610 --> 00:17:14,100
Every organization has bureaucracy, right?

406
00:17:14,100 --> 00:17:16,650
The way of doing things, that's a delay.

407
00:17:16,650 --> 00:17:18,410
Think about it, if you have
to onboard a bunch of people

408
00:17:18,410 --> 00:17:21,240
in the beginning of a
migration, then learning how

409
00:17:21,240 --> 00:17:23,880
just to navigate your organization

410
00:17:23,880 --> 00:17:26,610
is extra time that it's gonna take.

411
00:17:26,610 --> 00:17:29,310
And not having to hire them is great.

412
00:17:29,310 --> 00:17:30,630
The fact that they already work for you

413
00:17:30,630 --> 00:17:31,500
makes it a lot easier.

414
00:17:31,500 --> 00:17:34,020
So if, even just being purely selfish,

415
00:17:34,020 --> 00:17:36,000
'cause a lot of times it
sounds like I'm saying

416
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:37,650
invest in your employees as like charity.

417
00:17:37,650 --> 00:17:39,660
No, I'm saying do it for selfish reasons.

418
00:17:39,660 --> 00:17:42,790
It's gonna make your
migration more successful

419
00:17:43,680 --> 00:17:44,850
and you're gonna be able to operate it

420
00:17:44,850 --> 00:17:46,680
more successfully in the long term

421
00:17:46,680 --> 00:17:49,260
and it's gonna make your life easier.

422
00:17:49,260 --> 00:17:51,480
So it's easier to teach your cloud skills

423
00:17:51,480 --> 00:17:53,220
to your existing workforce

424
00:17:53,220 --> 00:17:55,410
than how your organization
works to external people.

425
00:17:55,410 --> 00:17:57,480
That's the key point there, right?

426
00:17:57,480 --> 00:17:59,700
And if you think about
that, it makes total sense.

427
00:17:59,700 --> 00:18:02,730
Cloud skills are a relatively
easy thing to learn,

428
00:18:02,730 --> 00:18:04,830
especially if you're giving
them opportunity to use it,

429
00:18:04,830 --> 00:18:06,270
which you should be doing,

430
00:18:06,270 --> 00:18:07,950
learning how your organization works?

431
00:18:07,950 --> 00:18:10,583
For some organizations, this
could be very difficult.

432
00:18:12,330 --> 00:18:15,840
Okay, so I'm making this
sound so easy, right?

433
00:18:15,840 --> 00:18:18,000
There are some problems, but
I'll give you some solutions.

434
00:18:18,000 --> 00:18:21,300
So the first problem is,
yeah, they're too busy, right?

435
00:18:21,300 --> 00:18:23,227
Every single time when you say

436
00:18:23,227 --> 00:18:25,110
"We're gonna let you do the migration,"

437
00:18:25,110 --> 00:18:27,360
they say, "We're too busy."

438
00:18:27,360 --> 00:18:29,370
They're telling you the truth, right?

439
00:18:29,370 --> 00:18:32,070
So my answer to that is, well
what are you so busy doing

440
00:18:32,070 --> 00:18:35,730
that you can't do a cloud
migration or cloud adoption

441
00:18:35,730 --> 00:18:37,080
or building this new app in the cloud

442
00:18:37,080 --> 00:18:39,300
or whatever the case may be.

443
00:18:39,300 --> 00:18:40,440
Whatever that answer is,

444
00:18:40,440 --> 00:18:42,450
outsource that, that's undifferentiated.

445
00:18:42,450 --> 00:18:45,630
That's stuff that you can
outsource at low cost.

446
00:18:45,630 --> 00:18:47,490
That's just keeping the lights on.

447
00:18:47,490 --> 00:18:49,740
Free up their time and
they'll appreciate it.

448
00:18:51,990 --> 00:18:56,700
Now the next one, they're
much less likely to vocalize,

449
00:18:56,700 --> 00:18:59,490
but it's typically true, they're fearful.

450
00:18:59,490 --> 00:19:00,570
What are they fearful of?

451
00:19:00,570 --> 00:19:02,970
They're fearful of the unknown.

452
00:19:02,970 --> 00:19:06,300
They're fearful "If I do
this, can I even do this?

453
00:19:06,300 --> 00:19:07,140
Am I gonna succeed?

454
00:19:07,140 --> 00:19:08,280
I've never done it before."

455
00:19:08,280 --> 00:19:09,193
For most people, when
they do a cloud migration,

456
00:19:09,193 --> 00:19:11,520
it's their first time doing it.

457
00:19:11,520 --> 00:19:12,900
So it's natural to be fearful.

458
00:19:12,900 --> 00:19:14,640
They're fearful "Will I have the skills

459
00:19:14,640 --> 00:19:16,923
to maintain this new cloud environment.

460
00:19:17,820 --> 00:19:19,230
Am I engineering myself out of a job?"

461
00:19:19,230 --> 00:19:23,400
There's a lot of things that
they have to be fearful of.

462
00:19:23,400 --> 00:19:25,950
So we need to address that.

463
00:19:25,950 --> 00:19:28,273
So give them a safety net, right?

464
00:19:28,273 --> 00:19:31,620
They might not vocalize it,
but they need the safety net.

465
00:19:31,620 --> 00:19:33,903
So give them training, lots of training,

466
00:19:36,000 --> 00:19:37,440
with a goal, right?

467
00:19:37,440 --> 00:19:38,730
They need to know going into the training

468
00:19:38,730 --> 00:19:41,280
that they're gonna be the
ones that are gonna drive,

469
00:19:41,280 --> 00:19:44,400
bring in experts, AWS
Solutions architects,

470
00:19:44,400 --> 00:19:46,770
professional services
partners, all these people

471
00:19:46,770 --> 00:19:49,270
who can help them and guide
them in the beginning.

472
00:19:50,400 --> 00:19:53,350
And you know, you really just
need to get buy in from them.

473
00:19:55,170 --> 00:19:57,000
And this kind of speaks to the last point.

474
00:19:57,000 --> 00:19:58,920
They may not even care, right?

475
00:19:58,920 --> 00:20:00,513
So we need to get them to care.

476
00:20:01,950 --> 00:20:05,010
If you're the boss and they work for you,

477
00:20:05,010 --> 00:20:08,910
they may like, want you to be successful,

478
00:20:08,910 --> 00:20:11,730
but I think if they have ownership of it,

479
00:20:11,730 --> 00:20:13,480
they're gonna be a little bit more,

480
00:20:15,780 --> 00:20:17,760
let's say receptive.

481
00:20:17,760 --> 00:20:21,960
So outsourcing to enable,
solve those first two problems,

482
00:20:21,960 --> 00:20:22,950
too busy and fearful.

483
00:20:22,950 --> 00:20:25,350
So let's talk about how
we solve this last one

484
00:20:25,350 --> 00:20:26,910
of them not caring.

485
00:20:26,910 --> 00:20:29,580
'Cause outsourcing itself
is rarely the problem,

486
00:20:29,580 --> 00:20:32,370
it's what we choose to
outsource that's the problem.

487
00:20:32,370 --> 00:20:35,070
We outsource the fun
stuff, the cloud migration,

488
00:20:35,070 --> 00:20:38,400
the building of the
new agenetic AI system.

489
00:20:38,400 --> 00:20:39,690
We're outsourcing that to people

490
00:20:39,690 --> 00:20:42,570
because we see the skills
gap in our organization.

491
00:20:42,570 --> 00:20:43,950
We should let our employees do that

492
00:20:43,950 --> 00:20:45,210
and we should outsource the boring stuff

493
00:20:45,210 --> 00:20:47,310
they don't want to do to make time for it.

494
00:20:48,450 --> 00:20:51,330
So how do we get buy-in?

495
00:20:51,330 --> 00:20:53,820
Because that's really what
we're talking about here.

496
00:20:53,820 --> 00:20:56,430
Well, I talked about a compelling why.

497
00:20:56,430 --> 00:20:57,600
You have to have a compelling why.

498
00:20:57,600 --> 00:20:59,100
It has to be something
they actually care about

499
00:20:59,100 --> 00:21:00,360
and it should be related to your industry.

500
00:21:00,360 --> 00:21:01,440
What does your company do?

501
00:21:01,440 --> 00:21:03,690
What does your organization do?

502
00:21:03,690 --> 00:21:06,960
Most leaders have this
advantage and they don't use it

503
00:21:06,960 --> 00:21:09,660
because they just don't know
how to articulate it, right?

504
00:21:09,660 --> 00:21:11,160
So for a live entertainment company,

505
00:21:11,160 --> 00:21:14,310
it might be we're making the
fan experience better, right?

506
00:21:14,310 --> 00:21:17,160
We're gonna make it easier to buy tickets.

507
00:21:17,160 --> 00:21:20,610
And we're going to make,
when you go to a concert,

