But yeah, they don't help us.

1013
00:40:44,430 --> 00:40:48,660
Now they might be useful
portfolio management strategies.

1014
00:40:48,660 --> 00:40:50,130
They certainly are, but
they don't have anything

1015
00:40:50,130 --> 00:40:52,350
to do with refactoring
and migration, right?

1016
00:40:52,350 --> 00:40:54,750
So they don't need to be made upfront.

1017
00:40:54,750 --> 00:40:57,330
We can make these decisions incrementally

1018
00:40:57,330 --> 00:40:59,100
or we can just not, these decisions

1019
00:40:59,100 --> 00:41:01,530
have nothing to do with
refactoring anyway.

1020
00:41:01,530 --> 00:41:04,680
Now, if we talk about the
things that are refactoring,

1021
00:41:04,680 --> 00:41:06,390
we have a couple choices

1022
00:41:06,390 --> 00:41:08,550
and neither of 'em, none of
them are really good, right?

1023
00:41:08,550 --> 00:41:10,530
So we have a full migration.

1024
00:41:10,530 --> 00:41:13,500
Refactor in the 7Rs language

1025
00:41:13,500 --> 00:41:15,810
means we're gonna change
the entire application.

1026
00:41:15,810 --> 00:41:17,100
This is a mainframe, right?

1027
00:41:17,100 --> 00:41:20,370
So I'd say that's like the
one of the very few examples

1028
00:41:20,370 --> 00:41:22,020
where you really have to do that.

1029
00:41:22,920 --> 00:41:24,570
But otherwise it's kind of a bad idea.

1030
00:41:24,570 --> 00:41:26,820
That's a lot of changes to
make while you're migrating,

1031
00:41:26,820 --> 00:41:28,080
a lot of things that could go wrong.

1032
00:41:28,080 --> 00:41:29,190
You could do it afterwards

1033
00:41:29,190 --> 00:41:31,290
and do it with all the tools in the cloud.

1034
00:41:32,220 --> 00:41:34,170
Then you have replatform,

1035
00:41:34,170 --> 00:41:37,713
which is a partial refactor, okay.

1036
00:41:39,715 --> 00:41:43,950
Rehost, which is no refactor,
known as a lift and shift.

1037
00:41:43,950 --> 00:41:47,100
And then this really oddball one relocate,

1038
00:41:47,100 --> 00:41:48,510
I think this was maybe
the most recent one.

1039
00:41:48,510 --> 00:41:50,340
I guess they wanted another R.

1040
00:41:50,340 --> 00:41:52,170
It's also a no refactor,

1041
00:41:52,170 --> 00:41:55,080
but from hypervisor like VMware, right?

1042
00:41:55,080 --> 00:41:56,017
The thing is, people could say,

1043
00:41:56,017 --> 00:41:57,150
"Well, those two are different."

1044
00:41:57,150 --> 00:41:59,520
But it doesn't represent a choice.

1045
00:41:59,520 --> 00:42:01,440
You don't get to choose
whether the application

1046
00:42:01,440 --> 00:42:04,170
is on hypervisor or not
or if it's physical.

1047
00:42:04,170 --> 00:42:07,380
So it's not a choice, so you
don't need another R for it.

1048
00:42:07,380 --> 00:42:09,540
So if remove the Rs that have
nothing to do with migration

1049
00:42:09,540 --> 00:42:12,330
and remove the redundant R, right?

1050
00:42:12,330 --> 00:42:14,010
We have three Rs left,

1051
00:42:14,010 --> 00:42:15,330
you see now, and we have a 3Rs model.

1052
00:42:15,330 --> 00:42:17,250
We've already simplified this.

1053
00:42:17,250 --> 00:42:19,440
But if you look at this,

1054
00:42:19,440 --> 00:42:20,760
something becomes very clear.

1055
00:42:20,760 --> 00:42:23,430
These 3Rs are nothing, they're not useful.

1056
00:42:23,430 --> 00:42:27,930
One is like a complete extreme refactor,

1057
00:42:27,930 --> 00:42:29,910
which you know you can do if you have to,

1058
00:42:29,910 --> 00:42:31,560
but otherwise it's probably a bad idea.

1059
00:42:31,560 --> 00:42:35,880
But it's a valid choice
if you want to do it.

1060
00:42:35,880 --> 00:42:38,520
You have a rehost, right?

1061
00:42:38,520 --> 00:42:40,740
A lift and shift, which
really doesn't exist

1062
00:42:40,740 --> 00:42:43,980
because you're not moving
your server to the cloud.

1063
00:42:43,980 --> 00:42:45,330
Migrate is a misnomer, right?

1064
00:42:45,330 --> 00:42:46,163
You're gonna rebuild it.

1065
00:42:46,163 --> 00:42:48,630
There's gonna be some
changes that are necessary.

1066
00:42:48,630 --> 00:42:51,930
And then you have well, replatform,

1067
00:42:51,930 --> 00:42:53,760
which is something, right?

1068
00:42:53,760 --> 00:42:55,680
Some amount of refactoring.

1069
00:42:55,680 --> 00:42:59,430
So what we find is that
there's not seven Rs.

1070
00:42:59,430 --> 00:43:01,020
It's really a spectrum, right?

1071
00:43:01,020 --> 00:43:04,020
It's an infinite spectrum of
how much refactoring we do.

1072
00:43:04,020 --> 00:43:05,880
Why are we choosing
these arbitrary buckets?

1073
00:43:05,880 --> 00:43:09,150
In fact, these buckets
don't help us at all, right?

1074
00:43:09,150 --> 00:43:12,270
We have rehost on one side,
refactor on the other,

1075
00:43:12,270 --> 00:43:15,570
which are very small edge
cases, if we think about it,

1076
00:43:15,570 --> 00:43:17,400
and then we have this
giant thing in the middle

1077
00:43:17,400 --> 00:43:20,370
called replatform, which doesn't give us

1078
00:43:20,370 --> 00:43:22,380
any meaningful guidance on what to do.

1079
00:43:22,380 --> 00:43:24,720
It just says we're
gonna make some changes,

1080
00:43:24,720 --> 00:43:26,280
but it doesn't say what
we're gonna change.

1081
00:43:26,280 --> 00:43:30,003
So it's really a 1R model,
we're gonna do something.

1082
00:43:30,930 --> 00:43:34,140
And yeah, I think a 1R model is good,

1083
00:43:34,140 --> 00:43:36,150
but I'm gonna rename it and call it MVR,

1084
00:43:36,150 --> 00:43:37,440
minimal viable refactoring.

1085
00:43:37,440 --> 00:43:41,160
Again, my favorite minimal viable thing

1086
00:43:41,160 --> 00:43:42,750
in this presentation.

1087
00:43:42,750 --> 00:43:44,190
So what we're gonna do is we're gonna do

1088
00:43:44,190 --> 00:43:46,260
the right amount of refactoring
to achieve our goal.

1089
00:43:46,260 --> 00:43:48,093
And we're gonna do it as we migrate.

1090
00:43:49,290 --> 00:43:51,570
So we're gonna do it iteratively.

1091
00:43:51,570 --> 00:43:54,540
This is gonna be flexible,
fast, simple, and safe

1092
00:43:54,540 --> 00:43:56,040
by doing it this way.

1093
00:43:56,040 --> 00:43:57,870
So we're gonna start
with a lift and shift,

1094
00:43:57,870 --> 00:43:58,950
conceptually, right?

1095
00:43:58,950 --> 00:44:00,780
We're gonna say, if we took this server

1096
00:44:00,780 --> 00:44:04,650
and we just rebuilt it exactly
how it is today in the cloud,

1097
00:44:04,650 --> 00:44:06,270
what would it look like?

1098
00:44:06,270 --> 00:44:09,600
And then we're gonna
realize that's not optimal.

1099
00:44:09,600 --> 00:44:12,090
So, 'cause some of the
things are gonna get worse,

1100
00:44:12,090 --> 00:44:14,430
so we're gonna do what I call
the hippocratic oath of IT.

1101
00:44:14,430 --> 00:44:16,320
First, do no harm, right?

1102
00:44:16,320 --> 00:44:19,080
We're gonna say for security, compliance,

1103
00:44:19,080 --> 00:44:21,630
reliability, performance, and cost,

1104
00:44:21,630 --> 00:44:23,310
we're gonna do just enough refactoring

1105
00:44:23,310 --> 00:44:28,020
to make those things
not worse, but no more.

1106
00:44:28,020 --> 00:44:30,000
And then we're gonna save
the rest of the refactoring

1107
00:44:30,000 --> 00:44:31,440
for after we're in the cloud,

1108
00:44:31,440 --> 00:44:33,480
because it's just so much
easier to do it then.

1109
00:44:33,480 --> 00:44:35,987
And we want to get this
migration thing done quickly,

1110
00:44:35,987 --> 00:44:39,120
'cause the migration is kind
of, it should be a non-event.

1111
00:44:39,120 --> 00:44:41,610
It shouldn't be this long drawn out thing.

1112
00:44:41,610 --> 00:44:43,890
The key is to get to the
cloud as quickly as possible

1113
00:44:43,890 --> 00:44:46,530
and do your refactoring in the cloud.

1114
00:44:46,530 --> 00:44:50,310
Okay, so now here's the
really animated last slide.

1115
00:44:50,310 --> 00:44:53,250
Well second to last slide,
what it looks like in practice.

1116
00:44:53,250 --> 00:44:56,040
And so what I mean by loosely
coupled, non-blocking.

1117
00:44:56,040 --> 00:44:57,603
Okay, here's our applications.

1118
00:44:58,440 --> 00:44:59,790
It goes in two stages.

1119
00:44:59,790 --> 00:45:01,620
So first stage is it goes, it gets scoped.

1120
00:45:01,620 --> 00:45:04,230
So a project manager
identifies the app owner,

1121
00:45:04,230 --> 00:45:06,450
QA tester, the infrastructure,
the dependencies,

1122
00:45:06,450 --> 00:45:08,070
all those other things
that we talked about.

1123
00:45:08,070 --> 00:45:09,360
They document it.

1124
00:45:09,360 --> 00:45:13,320
Cloud engineer takes the application

1125
00:45:13,320 --> 00:45:15,270
and designs cloud architecture for it,

1126
00:45:15,270 --> 00:45:16,680
which will be really easy
'cause we're gonna make it

1127
00:45:16,680 --> 00:45:19,080
very similar to what we have on prem.

1128
00:45:19,080 --> 00:45:22,080
It gets approved by the
application owner or stakeholder.

1129
00:45:22,080 --> 00:45:23,940
It gets built by the cloud engineer,

1130
00:45:23,940 --> 00:45:25,620
hopefully using infrastructure as code,

1131
00:45:25,620 --> 00:45:27,573
but that's optional.

1132
00:45:28,440 --> 00:45:30,600
At the same time you start
transferring the data.

1133
00:45:30,600 --> 00:45:33,300
So it's being built while
the data's being transferred.

1134
00:45:33,300 --> 00:45:35,160
When both of those things are done,

1135
00:45:35,160 --> 00:45:38,490
the app owner gets to do
their pre-cutover testing

1136
00:45:38,490 --> 00:45:40,290
and approve it, or not approve it

1137
00:45:40,290 --> 00:45:43,833
and say they approve it, you
cut it over and it goes live.

1138
00:45:45,079 --> 00:45:48,027
Now we've gotta take
all of our applications

1139
00:45:48,027 --> 00:45:50,760
and we gotta put it through
this process, right?

1140
00:45:50,760 --> 00:45:53,370
So this is the one thing I
needed help from the agency

1141
00:45:53,370 --> 00:45:55,080
to help with the animation here.

1142
00:45:55,080 --> 00:45:57,820
All right, so our monitoring
application gets scoped

1143
00:45:58,980 --> 00:46:02,730
while, well, it gets moved
to architecture design

1144
00:46:02,730 --> 00:46:04,290
while email gets scoped.

1145
00:46:04,290 --> 00:46:07,150
And you can see kind of how things move

1146
00:46:08,160 --> 00:46:10,110
through this pipeline.

1147
00:46:10,110 --> 00:46:14,580
Now, this is very simple
when nothing's blocked,

1148
00:46:14,580 --> 00:46:16,980
but as soon as, you know
something's gonna get blocked,

1149
00:46:16,980 --> 00:46:18,030
'cause it always does, right?

1150
00:46:18,030 --> 00:46:20,190
Let's say, okay, approval,

1151
00:46:20,190 --> 00:46:22,380
we're always get blocked
looking for approval, right?

1152
00:46:22,380 --> 00:46:23,520
This is very common.

1153
00:46:23,520 --> 00:46:26,640
The guy's on vacation or just
doesn't wanna approve it.

1154
00:46:26,640 --> 00:46:27,473
Doesn't like it.

1155
00:46:27,473 --> 00:46:28,440
So what are we gonna do?

1156
00:46:28,440 --> 00:46:29,940
Normally what ends up happening here

1157
00:46:29,940 --> 00:46:31,440
is the whole thing comes to a halt

1158
00:46:31,440 --> 00:46:33,480
and web, email and
monitoring will go live,

1159
00:46:33,480 --> 00:46:34,740
and then everything else waits.

1160
00:46:34,740 --> 00:46:38,070
But we're good engineers, we
realize there's five places

1161
00:46:38,070 --> 00:46:39,210
where things could get blocked,

1162
00:46:39,210 --> 00:46:41,130
and we're just gonna put a queue on there

1163
00:46:41,130 --> 00:46:42,540
and let things queue up.

1164
00:46:42,540 --> 00:46:44,924
So then we route around the problem.

1165
00:46:44,924 --> 00:46:47,460
Hey, file servers can
stay stuck in that queue

1166
00:46:47,460 --> 00:46:49,440
for as long as it we want

1167
00:46:49,440 --> 00:46:51,540
while payroll application gets moved.

1168
00:46:51,540 --> 00:46:55,050
And so everything goes
through the process.

1169
00:46:55,050 --> 00:46:56,250
We keep routing around the problem.

1170
00:46:56,250 --> 00:46:58,413
This is a simplified version of it.

1171
00:46:59,370 --> 00:47:00,660
In reality, there's gonna be things

1172
00:47:00,660 --> 00:47:02,280
queuing up all over the place.

1173
00:47:02,280 --> 00:47:04,350
The key is we want things to
move through this pipeline

1174
00:47:04,350 --> 00:47:05,700
as quickly as possible.

1175
00:47:05,700 --> 00:47:09,570
Eventually the, whatever
it is gets unblocked,

1176
00:47:09,570 --> 00:47:12,100
gets sequenced back in, and then

1177
00:47:13,740 --> 00:47:17,070
you move it through this
process until you're done.

1178
00:47:17,070 --> 00:47:20,070
This is basically how you can architect

1179
00:47:20,070 --> 00:47:22,620
the mechanics of a migration in a way

1180
00:47:22,620 --> 00:47:25,110
that can be done very quickly,

1181
00:47:25,110 --> 00:47:26,790
and the key is you're
not waiting on anyone.

1182
00:47:26,790 --> 00:47:28,773
Nobody's just sitting doing nothing.

1183
00:47:30,270 --> 00:47:32,790
So just the principles as a recap

1184
00:47:32,790 --> 00:47:34,950
and then hopefully we can
take a couple questions.

